"“Keep it there.”\n\n“My finger is numb.”\n\n“Then make it not numb.”\n\nHe rubbed his hand against his shirt, struck his fingertips into his palm, and tried again. His injured hip pressed against the wall to keep his weight off the left leg. The extinguisher hissed behind Julie. Its pressure began to fall.\n\nThe scan outline built from the center outward.\n\nMercer’s voice came through the cloud. “Reed, put down the cylinder.”\n\nMarcus kept discharging.\n\nThe team changed tactics. The shield descended until its lower edge nearly touched the floor, then advanced through the vapor by inches. One operator used the wall as a guide. Another called distances over the closed circuit in clipped numbers.\n\nThey did not need to see Marcus. They knew where the gate was.\n\nThe biometric outline reached Elias’s first knuckle and stopped.\n\nAPPLY STEADY PRESSURE\n\nHis finger shifted.\n\nThe image broke apart.\n\n“Don’t move,” Julie said.\n\n“I’m trying.”\n\n“Try without talking.”\n\nHe stared at the glass, shoulders rigid, and held the finger in place.\n\nThe extinguisher coughed.\n\nMarcus released the handles. The last white vapor drifted around him. He set the cylinder lengthwise against the inside corner where the corridor turned into the gate approach. It would not stop the shield. It would make the first operator step around it instead of driving straight through.\n\nThe panel chimed.\n\nLIVE BIOMETRIC CONFIRMED\n TOKEN PRIVATE KEY UNLOCKED\n\nThe circuit board’s display changed from the rotating digits to a single line.\n\nSIGNING LOCAL CHALLENGE\n\nElias exhaled through his teeth. “The private key never leaves the token. The panel sends a challenge. The secure element signs it only after the live match.”\n\nJulie watched the white cloud thin. “How long?”\n\n“It should already—”\n\nThe display updated.\n\nCHALLENGE RESPONSE VERIFIED\n EMERGENCY ACCESS RECORD PENDING\n\nA final screen replaced it.\n\nADMINISTRATOR: THORNE, ELIAS M.\n ROLE: ENCLAVE EMERGENCY ADMINISTRATOR\n ACTION: QUARANTINE GATE RELEASE\n\nCONTINUING WILL CREATE AN IMMUTABLE LOCAL AUDIT RECORD AND NOTIFY THE DESIGNATED SECURITY AUTHORITY.\n\nCONFIRM / CANCEL\n\nElias did not move.\n\nThe shield emerged from the vapor nine feet away.\n\nApex Security Command Center\n 04:56 Eastern Daylight Time\n\nThe enclave alarm reached Sarah Chen through a path the quarantine had been designed to preserve.\n\nA narrow amber box opened over the lower-tier schematic.\n\nEMERGENCY ADMINISTRATOR AUTHENTICATION\n THORNE, ELIAS M.\n REAR QUARANTINE GATE\n CHALLENGE RESPONSE VERIFIED\n FINAL CONFIRMATION PENDING\n\nSarah read it once.\n\nArthur Vance read it over her shoulder.\n\n“Stop him.”\n\nSarah keyed the closed-circuit channel. “Containment One, authentication has reached final confirmation. Prevent completion. Recover the telemetry intact. Do not strike the local panel or gate actuators.”\n\nMercer answered through background static. “Shield is inside nine feet. Subjects have discharged a clean-agent extinguisher. No visual on Reed.”\n\n“Less-lethal force authorized. Maintain ballistic hold unless you have an immediate threat to life.”\n\nVance leaned closer. “They are initiating active sabotage against a strategic production system.”\n\n“They are standing in front of the system you want protected.”\n\n“Then remove them from it.”\n\n“The team is doing that.”\n\nOn the schematic, the rear gate changed from white to pulsing amber. The command center could see the authentication state. It could not cancel it. Apex had built the enclave so a compromised corporate network could not override a local emergency administrator.\n\nVance understood the same limitation.\n\n“Authorize lethal force,” he said.\n\nSarah kept the channel open. “No.”\n\nThe word left no room for confusion.\n\nVance’s voice remained quiet. “Excuse me?”\n\n“A rifle round on that axis can enter the access panel, a locking actuator, or the independent control bus. If the gate faults between states, we lose containment and may corrupt the production environment.”\n\n“Thorne is about to open it.”\n\n“I can see that.”\n\n“Then the production environment is already at risk.”\n\n“Which is why I will not order a blind shot through suppressant vapor toward hardened machinery.”\n\nVance looked at the dark camera wall. “You are allowing procedure to become cover for them.”\n\nSarah watched the gate state.\n\n“No. I am preventing your urgency from destroying the evidence you claim you want secured.”\n\nHis eyes moved to her.\n\nThere was no accusation in his expression. Only calculation.\n\n“Prevent them from crossing,” he said. “Recover the case. Subject preservation is subordinate to recovery.”\n\nThe language was deliberate now.\n\nSarah keyed the team channel again. “Containment One, coordinated push. Shield lead. Separate Reed from the gate frame. Take O’Donnell and Thorne alive. Telemetry has priority. No rounds into the enclave axis.”\n\nShe had not repeated Vance’s last sentence.\n\nShe had still sent the team forward.\n\nProduction Enclave Approach\n 04:56 Eastern Daylight Time\n\nThe CONFIRM field waited beneath Elias’s name.\n\nJulie did not tell him to press it.\n\nMercer’s shield cleared the last of the vapor. The operator behind its right edge brought the electroshock weapon up, keeping the cartridge pointed away from the panel until he had a line on Marcus.\n\n“Elias,” Julie said.\n\nHis finger hovered over the screen.\n\n“If I do this, the record can’t be expunged.”\n\n“I know.”\n\n“It can’t be explained as credential replay. The private-key signature includes the biometric release event.”\n\n“I know.”\n\n“They can prosecute me from this screen.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\nMercer’s team took another step.\n\nElias looked at the case between Julie’s boots. Then at Marcus, bent around his damaged ribs beside an empty extinguisher, waiting for men with armor and weapons to reach him.\n\nHis hand shook hard enough that the tip of his finger moved in a small circle above the glass.\n\nHe pressed CONFIRM.\n\nThe panel gave a low two-note tone.\n\nEMERGENCY ACCESS COMMITTED\n AUDIT SEAL WRITTEN\n GATE RELEASE SEQUENCE ACTIVE\n\nThe first locking bolt retracted inside the wall with a metallic impact that Julie felt through the floor.\n\nThen the second.\n\nThen the third.\n\nSix bolts withdrew from alternating sides of the frame, each separated by a deliberate pause. The gate did not move.\n\n“Why isn’t it opening?” Marcus asked.\n\n“Independent power check,” Elias said.\n\nThe panel advanced.\n\nLOCK ARRAY CLEAR\n ACTUATOR POWER CONFIRMED\n PRESSURE EQUALIZATION ACTIVE\n\nA vent opened above the gate. Cold dry air moved outward across Julie’s face, carrying the faint smell of metal and filtered dust. On the panel, the pressure difference fell one number at a time.\n\n42 Pa.\n\nThe shield came forward.\n\nMarcus planted his good boot behind the empty extinguisher and waited.\n\n“Reed,” Mercer said. “Last chance.”\n\nMarcus looked at the shield. “You’ve said that twice.”\n\nThe lead operator drove forward.\n\nThe extinguisher rolled beneath the shield’s lower edge. It did not knock the operator down. It forced him to shorten his stride and lift the shield just enough to clear the cylinder.\n\nMarcus moved during that adjustment.\n\nHe caught the shield’s left rim with both hands and drove it into the inside wall of the corridor. The operator behind it absorbed the impact and kept his feet. Mercer stepped in from the right, using his shoulder to square the shield again.\n\nThe electroshock weapon appeared over the opposite edge.\n\n“Left high,” Julie called.\n\nMarcus released the shield and struck the operator’s wrist with his forearm. The cartridge discharged into the armored gate frame. Two barbed probes snapped against the steel and hung there on silver wires, sparking uselessly.\n\nMarcus backed two steps before the shield hit him.\n\nIts upper edge caught the ribs he had bruised on the bridge.\n\nHe folded around the impact. The lead operator kept pressure on him, using the shield as a moving wall rather than trying to strike past it. Mercer reached around the edge for Marcus’s right arm.\n\nMarcus turned with the grip instead of fighting it. He pulled Mercer half a step across the shield operator’s path and drove his own shoulder into the shield’s side.\n\nFor a moment, all three men occupied the same narrow space.\n\nThat was all Marcus needed.\n\nHe dropped his weight, twisted free, and retreated behind the armored gate frame.\n\nHe did not come away clean. A baton struck the outside of his right thigh as he moved. His torn boot slipped when the heel folded under him. He hit one knee beside Julie, one hand pressed hard against his ribs.\n\nThe team recovered its formation immediately.\n\nNo one chased him alone.\n\nOn the panel, the pressure difference reached zero.\n\nA heavy motor engaged behind the gate.\n\nThe two steel slabs shifted backward into their hinge housings by less than an inch. Then they began to pivot inward.\n\nA black seam appeared between them.\n\nTwo inches.\n\nFour.\n\nWhite floor light from inside the enclave cut through the opening.\n\nToo narrow for a hand carrying the case.\n\nToo narrow for a person.\n\nThe panel displayed:\n\nENTRY APERTURE: 102 MM\n FULL SERVICE OPEN: 44 SECONDS\n\nMarcus looked at the team regrouping six feet away.\n\n“We don’t have forty-four.”\n\n“We don’t need full open,” Julie said.\n\nShe studied the gate’s movement. Each slab rotated into a recessed arc inside the enclave. Yellow clearance lines glowed along the threshold. A second line on the panel showed the minimum safe aperture for personnel passage.\n\n560 MM.\n\nThe gate would reach it in twenty-one seconds.\n\nMercer saw the opening and changed the order.\n\n“Advance to the frame. Control Reed. Do not enter the hinge arcs.”\n\nProfessional. Specific. He understood the gate as well as Elias did.\n\nJulie moved the aluminum case to her left side and crouched beside Marcus.\n\n“Can you stand?”\n\n“Yes.”\n\n“That wasn’t the question.”\n\nHe put his good foot under him. “I can stand once.”\n\n“Make it the useful one.”\n\nThe shield drove toward them again.\n\nMarcus rose into it with his left shoulder against the gate frame. He did not try to stop the shield head-on. He let its edge pass him, caught the operator’s forearm when it appeared, and turned the arm into the steel jamb.\n\nThe movement cost him. The shield drove across his chest and pinned him long enough for Mercer to seize the back of his coveralls.\n\nJulie saw the next operator preparing to come around the shield’s left side.\n\n“Two behind,” she said. “Second one low.”\n\nMarcus stamped backward with the boot whose heel still held. His sole struck the lead operator’s shin, breaking the pressure for an instant. He tore free of Mercer’s grip and fell inside the depth of the gate frame.\n\nThe shield followed.\n\nIts top corner crossed the yellow clearance line.\n\nA warning sounded, and the gate stopped.\n\nHINGE ARC OBSTRUCTION\n ENTRY CYCLE HOLD\n\nThe operator pulled the shield clear. Two seconds later, the slabs resumed opening, but the entire front rank had been forced to stop and reset outside the frame.\n\nJulie understood the yellow lines now. They were not decoration. They marked the volume the armored leaves required to move. The team could control the corridor or enter the frame. It could not do both while carrying the shield.\n\n“Make them choose,” she told Marcus. “Shield or threshold.”\n\nThe aperture passed three hundred millimeters.\n\nOn the inner face of the right slab, a protected green paddle came into view.\n\nEMERGENCY CYCLE CONTROL\n\nJulie reached through the gap. Pain flared through her injured wrist when the moving steel forced her arm sideways. She got two fingers beneath the cover and flipped it open.\n\n“Close control,” she said. “Once we’re through, I can reverse the cycle.”\n\n“Not before,” Elias warned. “If it senses anyone in the threshold, it holds.”\n\nJulie looked at the shield.\n\nThat was the team’s next move. Put equipment or a body across the optical line, and the gate could not seal.\n\nThe aperture reached four hundred millimeters.\n\nMercer abandoned the shield.\n\nHe shoved it flat onto the floor instead of letting it block his own team, then stepped over it with the electroshock operator on his shoulder. The rifle stayed back. Chen’s ballistic hold was still in force.\n\nWithout the shield, they moved faster.\n\nMarcus met Mercer at the frame. He redirected the first reaching hand, caught the second at the wrist, and used the jamb to keep both men from turning their bodies fully into the fight. There was no room for punches with weight behind them. The struggle became forearms, shoulders, and boots searching for traction on the smooth floor.\n\nMercer’s taped wrist bent against the frame. He released and drove his other forearm into Marcus’s damaged ribs.\n\nMarcus lost his footing.\n\nThe electroshock operator came past Mercer with a fresh cartridge.\n\nJulie stepped in once, keeping the case tight against her left leg.\n\nShe caught the operator’s weapon hand with her injured right forearm and drove it down against the top edge of the discarded shield. The cartridge fired. One probe buried itself in the shield’s fabric cover. The other struck the floor and skittered beneath the gate.\n\nPain flashed from Julie’s thumb to her elbow. Her grip on the operator failed, but she backed away with the case still in her left hand. She had bought Marcus less than a second.\n\nHe used it.\n\nMarcus hooked one foot behind the abandoned shield and kicked it sideways. It rotated across the corridor, forcing Mercer and the electroshock operator to step back or be trapped against the frame. The rear team caught them and kept the formation from collapsing.\n\nThe gate reached five hundred millimeters.\n\nMINIMUM PERSONNEL APERTURE IN 3\n\n“Elias,” Julie said.\n\nHe stared through the widening seam at the white light beyond it.\n\n“Two,” she said.\n\nHis injured leg nearly failed when he shifted his weight.\n\n“One. Go.”\n\nThe panel chimed.\n\nMINIMUM PERSONNEL APERTURE\n\nThe token slot clicked and released the circuit board. Elias caught it against the panel with one shaking hand, then closed his fingers around it.\n\nHe turned sideways and entered between the moving slabs. His shoulder struck the right leaf. He twisted through, dragging his left leg after him, and fell against the inner wall.\n\n“Case.”\n\nJulie lifted the aluminum case edge-first. Her right hand could not take the weight. She shoved it through with her left forearm.\n\nElias caught the handle badly. The case hit the floor inside with a hard metallic knock.\n\nThe capture display stayed green.\n\nLOCAL MEDIA INTACT\n\nJulie followed it through. The gate’s steel edge passed inches from her back as the leaves continued opening. Inside, she seized the case with her left hand and turned.\n\nMarcus remained outside.\n\nMercer’s team surged together.\n\nTwo operators stepped over the shield while Mercer drove Marcus against the jamb. A forearm locked across Marcus’s upper chest. The electroshock weapon had no cartridge now, but the operator used its body as a striking tool and hammered it into Marcus’s right thigh where the baton had already landed.\n\nMarcus’s leg gave way.\n\n“Marcus.”\n\n“I’m moving.”\n\nHe was not.\n\nThe gate aperture reached six hundred millimeters. Wide enough for one unarmored person at a time. Not wide enough for two men fighting at the threshold.\n\nJulie set the case beyond the yellow line and went back.\n\nShe caught Marcus’s right wrist with both hands.\n\nPain shot through her own wrist so sharply that her grip weakened. She changed position, locking his forearm against hers instead of relying on her hand.\n\n“Elias.”\n\nHe pushed off the wall and grabbed the back of Marcus’s coveralls.\n\nMercer held the other side.\n\nMarcus became the line between them for one violent second.\n\nThe electroshock operator reached for Julie across his shoulder.\n\nMarcus drove his head backward into Mercer’s face. It was not a clean strike. The back of his skull glanced off Mercer’s cheek and split Marcus’s own scalp against the helmet rim, but Mercer’s grip loosened.\n\nJulie and Elias pulled.\n\nMarcus’s torn heel caught on the threshold.\n\nThe sole peeled away with a ripping sound. His foot came free of the boot opening just far enough to clear the optical line, leaving the damaged boot hanging half off.\n\nAll three fell inside.\n\nJulie rolled to the green paddle and struck it with the heel of her hand.\n\nENTRY CYCLE REVERSING\n\nThe motors changed pitch.\n\nThe steel slabs stopped, held, then began closing toward the center.\n\nMercer reached through the narrowing gap for Marcus’s coveralls. The optical line caught his arm and the motors paused. Marcus caught the wrist, turned it outward, and shoved it back into the corridor. The leaves resumed closing as soon as the threshold cleared.\n\nThe team did not fire. They did not throw a body into the hinge arc. Mercer pulled clear and ordered them off the threshold before the safety system could hold the gate open.\n\nThe white corridor became a narrowing vertical strip filled with weapon lights and dark armor.\n\nSarah Chen’s voice came through Mercer’s radio.\n\n“Do not damage the gate. Begin local override when it seals.”\n\nThen the slabs met.\n\nThe seam vanished.\n\nLocking bolts drove home in sequence. One. Two. Three. The impacts traveled through the floor until the sixth bolt seated and the motors went quiet.\n\nGATE SECURED\n EMERGENCY ENTRY COMPLETE\n\nThe enclave held still for half a second.\n\nThen Marcus rolled onto his back and drew one careful breath. Blood darkened the hair above his right ear. His boot hung open at the heel. One hand remained clamped over his ribs, and the muscle in his struck thigh jumped beneath the coveralls.\n\n“Conscious?” Julie asked.\n\n“Unfortunately.”\n\nElias sat against the wall with one leg extended. He looked at the circuit board clenched in one hand.\n\nA local display above it showed:\n\nEMERGENCY ACCESS RECORDED\n ADMINISTRATOR: THORNE, ELIAS M.\n AUDIT SEAL: COMMITTED\n\nHis name remained on the screen after every other status line cleared.\n\nMetal struck the outside of the gate.\n\nOnce. Pause. Twice.\n\nThe override pattern had begun again.\n\nJulie picked up the aluminum case.\n\nOnly then did she look beyond the entry chamber.\n\nThe production enclave was smaller than the machinery around it had suggested. A compact room extended thirty feet beyond the gate, lit by narrow white strips at floor level. Hardened cabinets occupied two walls. Fiber trunks and cooling lines disappeared beneath a raised service deck. There were no logos, no windows, and no wireless access points. Cold filtered air moved with barely any sound.\n\nTwo local terminals stood beneath an independent clock.\n\n04:58:11\n\nThe machines had continued working through the pursuit, the quarantine, and the fight outside their door.\n\nThe recovery console awakened as the authenticated gate session registered inside the enclave.\n\nEMERGENCY PROVENANCE RECOVERY\n PRESENT DISPUTED OPERATIONAL SOURCE\n\nJulie held the case but did not open it.\n\nA second display came alive above the console.\n\nARGUS STRATEGIC RELEASE\n ASSESSMENT STATE: VALIDATED\n FINALIZATION ACTIVE\n EXTERNAL COMMIT QUEUE: ARMED\n\nThe last line populated a moment later.\n\nTIME TO EXTERNAL COMMIT: 01:37\n\nMarcus pushed himself onto one elbow. Elias stared at the number as if the panel had made an arithmetic error.\n\nOutside, the override tool struck the gate a third time.\n\nOnscreen, 01:37 became 01:36.\n\nThe gate had cost them three minutes. Argus had used every one.\n\n---\n\n# Chapter 8 - The 05:00 Abort\n\nApex Building Three\nReston, Virginia\n04:58 Eastern Daylight Time\n\nJulie set the aluminum case beneath the recovery console and turned it so the cable bay faced the wall.\n\nThe movement required both hands. Her right wrist failed halfway through, sending a hot line of pain into her thumb, and the case dropped the final inch onto the raised floor.\n\n“Elias. Port.”\n\nHe pushed himself upright against the wall. His left leg resisted when he tried to put weight on it, and he crossed the short distance with one hand sliding along a cabinet. The thin circuit board remained clenched in the other.\n\nMarcus rolled onto his side near the gate.\n\nJulie looked at him once. Blood had reached the collar behind his right ear. His damaged boot sat crooked on his foot, the peeled heel opening and closing when he moved. He drew each breath around the ribs instead of through them.\n\n“Stay down,” she said.\n\n“I can watch a door from the floor.”\n\n“Then watch it.”\n\nAnother metallic impact struck the outer face of the gate. The sound carried through the six locking bolts and into the deck beneath Julie’s knees.\n\nA narrow status strip beside the interior cycle control changed from green to amber.\n\nLOCAL OVERRIDE DETECTED\n LOCK ARRAY PRESSURE TEST\n\nMarcus read it. “They’ve started on the bolts.”\n\nAbove the recovery console, the release clock continued.\n\n01:31.\n\nElias reached the terminal and stared across its blank lower panel.\n\n“It should have a forensic input behind the service cover.”\n\n“Should?”\n\n“The console was commissioned after my team’s last recovery exercise.” He pressed beneath the left edge, then the right. Nothing opened. “They changed the housing.”\n\nJulie swept her fingers along the seam. No latch. No fastener. The metal face was interrupted only by a recessed symbol showing two opposing arrows around a sealed square.\n\n“Incident media,” she said.\n\nElias leaned closer. “Press and hold.”\n\nShe used her left thumb.\n\nA section of the panel withdrew and slid sideways. Inside were two shielded receptacles: one shaped for an evidence-device connector, the other a narrow copper-edge slot like the gate panel outside.\n\nThe console updated.\n\nFORENSIC INCIDENT INPUT AVAILABLE\n MEDIA WILL MOUNT IN PROTECTED MODE\n NO PRODUCTION WRITE PATH PRESENT\n\nJulie opened the case.\n\nThe left latch released under her thumb. The right required pressure her injured hand could not give. She changed angle, braced the case with her knee, and forced the latch with the heel of her palm. Pain ran up her forearm, but the metal catch lifted.\n\nInside, the government evidence drive remained seated in its foam cradle. The shielded cable lay coiled in the lid compartment where she had secured it after the motel review. The small case display still showed green.\n\nCAPTURE SEALED\n LOCAL MEDIA INTACT\n\n“Read-only?” she asked.\n\n“The protected port has no route into production memory,” Elias said. “It copies selected blocks into a local reconciliation workspace. If the isolation controller is functioning.”\n\nJulie looked at the screen.\n\n“Can we verify that before connection?”\n\nElias’s fingers moved over the console, too fast at first. His cut right index left a small dark mark on the glass. He stopped, wiped the blood against his shirt, and used his left hand instead.\n\nA topology diagram appeared. The incident input terminated inside a boxed recovery partition. A one-way arrow pointed from the live operational archive into the same partition. Nothing pointed back until a final object labeled PROVENANCE DECISION.\n\n“The comparison can alter source status,” Elias said. “It cannot write packet content into the feed.”\n\n“Good.”\n\n“Julie, once it withdraws provenance, every conclusion built from that source can be suspended.”\n\n“That’s why we came.”\n\n“It can also withdraw conclusions that happen to be right.”\n\n“I know.”\n\nThe clock reached 01:12.\n\nJulie removed the cable and seated one end in the case. Her right hand could not hold the collar steady. Marcus dragged himself closer, using the cabinet base and his good heel.\n\n“Give it here.”\n\n“You’re watching the gate.”\n\n“I can do two things badly.”\n\nHe took the connector in one hand while Julie aligned the key with her left. Together they locked it into place. Marcus looped the cable beneath the case handle so a pull at the console would not tear it from the evidence drive.\n\n“Gate,” Julie said.\n\nHe shifted back until he could see the amber strip. The movement tightened his face, but he made no sound.\n\nJulie plugged the other end into the protected receptacle.\n\nThe console detected the case immediately.\n\nSEALED INCIDENT CAPTURE DETECTED\n SESSION: REED-OVERSIGHT-117\n NETWORK VERIFICATION: UNAVAILABLE\n\nMOUNT MODE\n READ-ONLY / DUPLICATE / INGEST\n\n"